This paper is likely to belong to the cs.DB (databases) sub-category as it deals with outlier detection in real-world KDD (knowledge discovery in databases) applications. It also involves the analysis of data patterns and parameter settings, which are important aspects of database research. 

The paper also involves machine learning techniques such as distance-based methods, which are commonly used in the cs.LG (machine learning) sub-category. 

The cs.DS (data structures and algorithms) sub-category is also a possibility as the paper deals with the relative location of objects and their neighbours, which is a fundamental concept in data structures. 

The cs.AI (artificial intelligence) sub-category is another possibility as outlier detection is a common task in AI applications, and the paper involves the development of a new approach for this task. 

Finally, the cs.CR (cryptography and security) sub-category is a less likely possibility as the paper does not explicitly deal with security or cryptography, but outlier detection is also a relevant task in security applications.
